      <div id="ContentBody" class="HasColumn"> 
       <h1>Partnership Results in a Study Quantifying Air Pollution’s Severe Health Costs in India </h1> 
       <div class="Date">
        March 2, 2015
       </div> 
       <div class="Author">
        By Robert Rosenbaum, Evidence for Policy Design 
       </div> 
       <span class="ezoe"><p>India’s air pollution is among the worst in the world, as ranked by the World Health Organization (WHO). Now, a Harvard Kennedy School professor is helping to bring the massive scale of the problem to public attention and test possible solutions.</p><p>A new <a href="http://www.epw.in/special-articles/lower-pollution-longer-lives.html" target="_self">study</a> published in this week’s<i>&nbsp;Economic &amp; Political Weekly </i>shows that India’s high air pollution has pernicious health consequences for nearly every person in India. The study, led by <a href="http://www.hks.harvard.edu/about/faculty-staff-directory/rohini-pande" target="_self">Rohini Pande</a>, Mohammed Kamal Professor of Public Policy, and collaborators from Harvard, University of Chicago, and Yale, shows that over half of India’s population – 660 million people – live in areas where fine particulate matter pollution is above India’s standards for what is considered safe. Furthermore, 99.5 percent live in areas with air pollution above the WHO’s stricter guidelines for healthy air.</p><p>The researchers find that if India met its own air standards, those 660 million people would add about 3.2 years onto their lives. Put another way, lack of compliance with Indian air quality standards is costing the country’s citizens 2.1 billion life-years.</p> 
        <div class="">
         <div class="content-view-embed embed-image class-image"> 
          <div class="attribute-image"> 
           <img src="/var/ezp_site/storage/images/media/images/india-pollution-map/1694485-1-eng-US/india-pollution-map.png" width="400" height="400" class="" alt="" title=""> 
          </div> 
         </div> 
        </div><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Our policy recommendations, therefore, are not for the Indian government to drastically change their pollution standards, as some may suggest,” said Pande. “Rather, we recommend the government take action to better enforce the regulations already on the books. Specifically, we suggest that India adopt improved monitoring techniques and technologies, create a punitive system that allows for fines rather than just criminal penalties, and adopt a market-based regulatory regime, such as a cap-and-trade system, for industrial pollution.”</p><p>To accomplish this, Pande and her team of researchers are working alongside government officials to design and test policy reforms.</p><p>“We believe that research, especially research with clear policy implications, cannot happen in a vacuum. It must be conducted with policy partners who have the ability and incentive to actually implement the results,” Pande said.</p><p>Since 2012, this group of researchers has been working with the Indian Government to develop reforms that can help bring Indian air pollution under control. The partnership began with a study of the audit system used by the Gujarat Pollution Control Board.</p><p>The results were striking. The system created a clear conflict of interest for auditors, who were paid by firms but reported to the state; however, modest changes in system design drastically decreased corruption in audit reports and led firms to cut pollution. The recommendations from this research were recently <a href="http://www.hks.harvard.edu/news-events/news/articles/gujarat-pollution-emission-reforms" target="_self">incorporated into Gujarat policy</a>, and the team continues to work with the state and national government to design, test and implement economically sound reforms to the regulatory system.</p><p>In the current phase of this partnership, researchers are testing whether improved information flows to the regulator via continuous emissions monitoring devices (probes that are installed into the smoke stacks of factories to capture pollution output levels) can have an impact on the government’s regulatory capacity.</p><p>As the team moves forward, they plan to use these findings to help the government design an emissions trading scheme – i.e. a cap-and-trade system – to ensure that pollution abatement will coexist with high levels of economic growth. At Harvard, researchers on this project are based at <a href="http://epod.cid.harvard.edu/" target="_self">Evidence for Policy Design</a>, a research program that Professor Pande co-directs at the Center for International Development, along with the <a href="http://www.hks.harvard.edu/centers/mrcbg/programs/sustsci" target="_self">Sustainability Science Program</a> (SSP).</p><p>Two of the study's co-authors, Janhavi Nilekani and Anish Sugathan, are currently SSP Fellows, while Nick Ryan of Yale and Anant Sudarshan of the University of Chicago are former SSP fellows. In India, a field team of Research Associates is based out of the Jameel Lateef Poverty Action Lab, where they meet regularly with government officials and conduct rigorous analysis of incoming data.</p></span> 
       <div class="tags"> 
        <div class="attribute-tags_geography">
         <label>Geographies:</label> 
         <p>Tags: <img class="transparent-png-icon" src="/extension/eztags/design/standard/images/tag_icons/small/empty.png" title="India" alt="India"> <a href="/tags/view/Geographies/India">India</a> </p>
        </div> 
        <div class="attribute-tags_topic">
         <label>Issues &amp; Topics:</label> 
         <p>Tags: <img class="transparent-png-icon" src="/extension/eztags/design/standard/images/tag_icons/small/empty.png" title="Health" alt="Health"> <a href="/tags/view/Issues%2C+Topics+and+Policy/Health">Health</a> , <img class="transparent-png-icon" src="/extension/eztags/design/standard/images/tag_icons/small/empty.png" title="Health Policy" alt="Health Policy"> <a href="/tags/view/Issues%2C+Topics+and+Policy/Health+Policy">Health Policy</a> </p>
        </div> 
       </div> 
      </div> 
